Vice President Kamala Harris delivered a speech at the South Lawn, highlighting the progress made by the Biden administration in delivering on their promise to take action and build a better America. She mentioned the challenges faced during the pandemic and praised the resilience of the American people. Harris also emphasized the importance of investing in infrastructure and shared a personal story about a child affected by lead exposure, highlighting the administration's commitment to removing lead pipes in America. She then shifted focus to the Inflation Reduction Act, which she said would benefit millions of Americans. Lastly, Harris praised President Biden's leadership on climate change and thanked him for his vision and faith in America's potential. The speech concluded with the introduction of Lovette Jacobs, a union worker from Boston.